##HTML input
Using input elements enables developers to create interactive websites. To create an input element, we use the <input> tag and specify the type of input using the "type" attribute.

#Why use HTML input elements?
1.Captures data from user for processing.
2.Used to parse data to the back-end.
3.Shape the client and server response.

##Basic HTML Input Types

1. text – single line text input
syntax:
<input type="text" placeholder="Enter name">

2.password – hides typed characters
syntax:
<input type="password" placeholder="Enter password">


3.email – validates email format or A text field that accepts a single line of text. The text is treated as an email address and uses validation parameters.
syntax:
<input type="email" placeholder="Enter email">


4.number – only numeric input allowed
syntax:
<input type="number" min="1" max="100">


5.tel – for phone numbers
syntax:
<input type="tel" placeholder="Phone number">

6.url – accepts website links
syntax:
<input type="url" placeholder="Enter website">

-->Date & Time Inputs=>(Generates a simple UI which allows users to select a time and date.

1.date – calendar date picker
syntax:
<input type="date">

syntax:
time – time picker
<input type="time">

2.datetime-local – date + time
<input type="datetime-local">


3.month – select month & year
syntax:
<input type="month">

4.week – select week number
syntax:
<input type="week">

-->Selection Inputs

1.radio – choose one option
syntax:
<input type="radio" name="gender"> Male
<input type="radio" name="gender"> Female


2.checkbox – select multiple options
syntax:
<input type="checkbox"> Java
<input type="checkbox"> Python

3.file – upload file
syntax:
<input type="file">

4.color – color picker
syntax:
<input type="color">

-->Button Inputs

1.submit – submits form or A clickable button that submits form data.
syntax:
<input type="submit" value="Send">

2.reset – resets form values
syntax:
<input type="reset">

2.button – clickable button (JS use)
syntax:
<input type="button" value="Click">

-->Range & Hidden

1.range – Enables users to select between a maximum and minimum range.
syntax:
<input type="range" min="0" max="100">


2.hidden – invisible field (stores data)
syntax:
<input type="hidden" value="userID123">